Apparently specific color suit individiual car models from specific years better others. Whoever designs a car like this, benefits from a value gain.

Partial Effect Interaction Plot: Color*Seller Type

It seems that private sellers do not realize the effect of color popularity. They overprice individual, unpopular colors vs.professional sellers and underprice popular colors. Professional sellers seem to have a feeling for which color works for which model.

## NOTE: privatesellercolpopPYPM does not appear in the model
## NOTE: privatesellercolpopPYPM is not a high-order term in the model

Partial Effect Interaction Plot: Color*Time

It seems that popular colors only increase a cars value during the first couple of years. This value then diminishes (or reverts) over time. Why it does revert does not make sense to me.

## NOTE: sqrt(ageindays)colpopPYPM is not a high-order term in the model

Partial Effect Interaction Plot: Color x Time x PrivateSeller

This plot does not add a lot. What can be seen is that professional sellers (Plot 0) price better for popular colors initially and then the relationship inverts later and the inversion is less extreme.

## NOTE: privatesellercolpopPYPMsqrt(ageindays) is not a high-order term in the model
